segments.text: Do you remember any special speakers, any important campus celebrities coming to visit the campus during your student days?
The president, the governor, a general?
They probably did.
But you don't?
But right now, there's nothing that jumps out.
Nothing stands out at all.
Commencement, where was it?
Tell me about commencement, when you graduated.
Commencement was over in G. Robin.
And it was hot.
And had the chairs on the floor.
And the stage up on the end, down against the wall.
And that's where commencement was held.
Do you remember who the speaker was?
No.
I'm sure that somewhere I probably had that ceremony filed.
My mother did.
Who came for you?
Well, my mom and my daddy came.
And my daddy had some sisters, and they were very close to me.
And one of my favorite aunt, my oldest aunt, came down there.
She had lost her husband, and she came and brought her boy.
And I think that was it.
I don't remember my brothers.
They probably were.
And you attended?
Everybody attended graduation.
I don't know of anybody that didn't go to graduation.
Name was called, and hands were shaking.
I guess, because I just don't remember people not being there.
The student organizations, what were the important student organizations that you remember?
Well the schools had theirs and they had a fishing game club and I was not real active in that but I went.
The schools had those.
The Hometown Club, in my experience, was the big, big organization.
They had others.
What about band, scene cadets?
Oh, yeah.
I don't remember scene cadets.
Clearly, if you said that you know for a fact that scene cadets were there, I would say not for a fact, but I'm almost sure they were.
I'm virtually certain of it.
Band, of course, has always been a big thing.
Always been.
Corps cadets was the predominant thing there.
What was the most prestigious...
student office, student position?
Oh, probably Cadet Colonel Coole.
That's the one everybody knew Auburn knew.
And what were the other?
Probably President's student body, although frankly, I don't recall who that was.
Head yell leader?
Head yell leader, of course, was, yell leaders were all known.
Head yell leader, you know, that's exactly why I wasn't thinking of that.
Yell leaders were just the, just that.
The student body followed them.
You know, they'd give directions and everybody would follow.
A lot of authority given to those guys in those days.
I mean, I'm talking about crowd control, anything like that.
They did a great job.
Let's see, describe, since the,
Aggie football team's doing pretty well in those years.
Well, they didn't do so well when I was there.
It was after I left.
I mean, right before I got there.
Barry Bryant was there.
He left the semester.
I mean, he coached the last semester.
That's what I thought, yeah.
My first semester.
He coached that team.
The 57th.
And they did do great that year.
They lost three games that year.
Describe a typical Aggie football, home football Saturday.
Well, if you were lucky, you had a date down there.
And I had some dates to football games.
Always a big weekend.
Looking forward to that.
They sold the Aggie mugs.
Remember those deals?
They'd go to the TAM or something.
You basically always got one of those.
They weren't expensive.
I don't know what they cost, but you got one of those.
Girls would come in either in car, which is not uncommon.
I mean, they came in as groups, you know, something like that.
Commonly, we would pick girls up the train at North Zooch.
Had one guy that had a car, an old one, and the back door was tied closed with a rope.
And the car's name was Old Blue.
We'd get in Old Blue and take off up there on Friday.
And the train was always late.
We'd try to get back from Midnight Yale and step over to Grove.
Pick those girls up at North Sage and take off back down there to Midnight Yale.
And then there was a place, we'd a lot of times go up to Falcon Lounge or the old Bryan Air Base.
There was a place up in that club up there called Falcon Lounge.
We'd end up going up there.
We'd get them usually rooms over at the Sabre Motel somewhere around North, not North Gate, East Gate of that area.
And they'd stay up there.
Now was it the responsibility of the Aggie to pay that room?
Oh everything.
The Aggie paid it all.
We split it up or whatever.
And gosh it may cost $7 a night.
Did many people have tessie dates?
You know they did.
I've heard about writing a blind date.
That was not unusual to go to a town and show up and you know somebody to get dates for.
You went to Austin several times.
Somebody had a car or even hitchhike over there and see some T-Cit friend and get dates over there.
And one old boy met some girls that worked at a telephone company.
I mean, we went to holler one Saturday afternoon, let's go to Austin.
I had, I think, one sport coat and one pair of pants or something like that.
We took off over there and dated some girls that worked at a telephone company and drove back the next morning before daylight or something.
Tessie's were, they came to campus a lot.
Guys that come to Dallas for the football game, TCU, Fort Worth, and Dallas over there, it was not rare to go up to North Texas, walk in the dorm and sit with three of us here and watch the Bates.
And then the girls come downstairs and they sort of pick them out, you know.
That was not unusual.
Tell me about Midnight Yale practice.
It was a great experience.
A lot of Bates were there because of the football games, you know, we had them come in there.
go to Midnight Yale.
I'm not saying drinking was not a problem, but I remember it being a problem.
I think today they'd be having trouble drinking there, and I don't know that it wasn't, but I remember thinking about that.
But we'd go to the Grove, and Midnight Yale was a big thing to go to.
All the girls wanted to go there, and it never occurred to us not to go to Midnight Yale practice.
Just like silver taps or something, you would never consider not going to silver taps.
It was just not done.
But the Midnight Yales, you'd go to that, and after that we'd go out somewhere,
and go to bed at all hours.
Next morning, probably pick up those girls up and maybe, and probably go to Sabisa with them.
Took her to Sabisa quite a bit.
And ate over there.
Didn't go to restaurants that much.
Some, the Triangle or something maybe.
But maybe for the football game, go there.
Parents would come down sometime.
You'd buy tickets and they'd go into Sabisa.
We always kind of wanted to show it off.
It was kind of cool.
You know, call all that food by nicknames.
Then on Saturday night, was there usually an organized campus social event on a Saturday night after a game?
Probably was.
I don't remember that.
I don't remember going to that.
We'd gather.
You know, big groups would have dates down.
Or maybe all get adjoining rooms at the holiday end.
But down on Texas, there's some hotels along there, motels.
And get several rooms together.
We'd all go back over there.
In the early part of the year, they'd have swimming pools.
We'd go swimming.
You know, spent some time together.
Do you know anything about any, did you hear anything about secret fraternities?
Well, that's not right.
Back in those days, Judge McDonnell had ruled something out.
It would be women admitted or something like that.
Harrington was there and Rutter and those guys were there.
There was a group called the Molds and they published
the mole in the steam tunnels, an underground, literally, newspaper.
And you'd find those things over by selling, you know, they'd be over there in stacks or whatever, and the mole would come out.
It was a controversial student-published sheet, you know, like that.
And it would, you know, want to hang the Harrington effigy or whatever they even did.
Was the mole conservative?
Ultra.
So it was against any change.
Any change, that's right.
Any change at all.
And we all got, it was a big laughing matter, got a kick out of it.
Secret fraternities as such, though.
I don't remember anything.
Some of the people that I've chatted with so far have said yes, they thought there was the TTs, the True Texans, and that there were another group said they thought there was one called the Stickers.
as in the last two syllables of swastika.

And I have found that in old Longhorn yearbooks, remember that was the name until 48, quite often there was a swastika, long before Adolf Hitler used it, came from the Navajo symbolism for friendship.
Right.
and that there would be a swastika drawn on various things.
I have no idea where they're... Now, if you ask me if I've heard of that, I have heard of those.
But you don't...
But I wasn't aware of anything like that.
And if you ask me how long ago have you heard of this, I've heard of this since I've been on the board of the Association of Farmers.
Okay.
All right.
I've even heard a few people go so far as to drop a couple of names that it'd be very surprising how profiled names they might have had to distance.
I wouldn't dare repeat those because I wouldn't even know if that's the case or not.
I don't know the implication of those secret fraternities.
There have been indications of it.
Back to the routine of social life.
In all of these dances and midnight yell practices and so forth,
non-regs, and corps members participate fully, equally?
Probably not.
I think that's the reason that I didn't have the experience with the organized things.
Now, I'm not saying anybody's at fault here, except myself.
I don't remember, for example, ever having gone to a cotton ball.
It's a big thing in spring.
The mate of cotton was chosen down there.
Big thing.
The beautiful girls would come by.
We'd sit by and watch and lust, I guess, you know, and watch those pretty girls come by.
And they had pictures in the annual, you know, so...
Well, but I didn't participate in it.
But you went to, y'all practiced, and you went to, and you and your buddies went to Senior Taps, to Silver Taps.
Always.
You participated in those things without fail.
Let's see, no World War II, no back, were there some veterans there from Korea days that you remember?
Some quote older guys?
Yeah, they were in the wildlife department.
We had some fellows that came back and were studying wildlife.
They were veterans.
As a matter of fact, there were quite a number of undergraduates who were veterans at that time.
They were mainly day ducks.
They were guys who had come back and lived off campus.
Many were married by that time.
Now, how did you learn Aggie slang?
by osmosis?
Well, probably not.
Probably learned a lot of it, because like I say, when you decide to go to A&M, you start getting all this literature, you know.
I mean, they'd come out and they probably had little booklets.
I was aware of much of that when I got there, but for the most part, it was probably just exposure to the ones they got on campus.
Quite a lot of trivia.
You were in non-reg, you learned quite a lot of trivia.
You weren't held accountable for it, but you were exposed to it.
And, uh,

that you were pretty doggone well versed as a non-reg down there because it was such a traditional closed society that you were around this stuff all the time and you know you were surrounded by core guys and other non-regs and it was just there wasn't you did not speak to each other you were good friends with those fellas spent a lot of time in that dorm room and stuff like that uh harrington was a senior administrator did you as a student have any interaction seeing
I don't know.
Did you have any impression?
See him occasionally.
He would be at things.
He'd be at functions.
I'm sure he occasionally would be at... What was your memory of his personality?
He was regarded as probably a very starchy fellow in those days.
Maybe controversially, though.
Rudder was adored, of course, like you.
You think he was adored even then?
I think so.
But he endeared himself.
I mean, I had a, I was on crutches one time, I had a hurt foot, and I was walking along there on crutches, and it was raining, and a car pulled up over there by Salisa Hall.
I was over in 16, and over close where the fountain is now.
A car pulled up, the door opened, and I leaned down because I was ringing the way I try to handle those books and stuff, you know, out of that poncho.
And President Lutter was there.
He said, where are you going, son?
I said, well, I'm trying to get to my dorm.
He said, well, get in.
I'll take you.
I said, just right over there.
He said, I'll take you.
So I got in the car with him.
We visited on the way over there.
We sat down and visited a few times.
Unusual.
Unusual.
That kind of a, maybe it wasn't unusual in those days.
But I thought it, we're sitting here talking about 40 years later.
I obviously remember.
Was there a guy named Pinky Downs there then?
Describe Pinky.
Boy, he was quite a figure, I'm telling you.
I think he wore an old black hat, kind of a flat brimmed hat, kind of a tall crown to it.
He was an old man, didn't he?
And he was everywhere.
He was at yoke practices and football games and
And I'll tell you, he was quite a character.
The official greeter was what he was called.
So in a lot of time around the all-face chapel, MSC, all through there, you'd see him.
He'd come into the dorm.
But you'd notice him.
I mean, it's like Ichabod Crane showed up.
You'd look up, and he was such an imposing guy.
I wouldn't say imposing.
Noticeable.
But he was just ubiquitous.
You know, piggy-downs on campus.
J.E.
Lupo?
Oh, yeah.
Love most of my books over there.
Walk in, always spoke to everybody, give you a dollar for your friendship, and you buy a book, and he'd knock a dollar off or something like that.
Always knew that, you know.
But later on, I bought my vet school supplies and went from there.
Interesting man.
May never be another one like him.
Now, I've heard that many students could buy things on credit from you.
I didn't, but that was done many times.
Hired a lot of students.
Let student organizations that sold instruments, for example, vet school, get supplies, I think, through himself.
Like he told me one time, a long years ago, he said, I don't believe I've ever lost any money in student loans.
I've heard he said that.
Now, I didn't know Lupo.
personally, like I know you even.
We have visited many, many, many times, but all students just about at that day could say that.
But when you got ready to go to A&M, you started getting your package in the mail.
Lupo was there.
I mean, his presence was high from that point on.
He really did a great job of marketing himself down there.
Let's see, other characters.
There wasn't a dean of students then.
There wasn't a John Coldis-like character, was there?
There was a phone named Benny Zinn.
Yeah, yeah, I forgot Benny.
And Benny Zinn was a guy that you all, everybody knew about him.
And I know we had a big water fight one time.
You're not supposed to have those on water.
He had a big water fight.
He came over and walked around for a while.
He said, I want this thing cleaned up, and I don't want this happening anymore because it'll catch anybody and kick them out of school, kind of like that.

Also, we had a little bunch of, I remember vaguely, Pascoe, that we had some guys that registered at A&M that were just a little bit, I mean they were kind of a troublemaker, a liberal faction that came in and had an organization name, I think, that was national on college campuses.
And I can't remember the name of that.
Supposedly some of those guys registered before, moved into a dorm.
Anything to be different, they would challenge everything.
Rumor has it that a bunch of Aggies got those guys down to give them a GI shower.
You know, got those brushes and just scrubbed them down real good.
They even bathed that long hair, kind of one of those deals.
Probably some of those guys, like Dr., I mean Mr.
Rudder said at the steps, you'll have to get by this pot better than the president before you're going to do this.
That attitude.
And I think that Zen or somebody got over there and told him, said you are, you cannot do that.
You are confined to this campus for the rest of the night.
and nothing, in other words, a cursory approval almost.
Those guys didn't stay.
Let's see, other, Dean of Agriculture was there?
Dr. Potts is such a prominent fellow in my mind.
He was not Dean of Agriculture, but Dean of Agriculture I know
was a big figure in those days.
But you as a student didn't have it?
As a student, I had nothing, no dealings with it.
Let's see, describe Northgate.
What was at Northgate?
Probably, much like today, is one of the worst things on grade points you ever saw in your life.
That was the nearest thing we had for commercial enterprise around there.
You know, you always go to the post office.
and go to the post office when there's no reason in the world not to go on over and get a cup of coffee.
Go get a cup, as everybody said.
There was no liquor store in that gate.
And where would you get that coffee?
Oh, there was a place called Godfrey's over there.
The bookstores, there were two or three bookstores over there.
The photo shop was in the corner.
The boot store, the shoe store, sockage or whatever it was named.
Hollick's?
Hollick's, yeah, it was down there.
Ellison Drug was on the corner right across over there in the south, I mean on the northwest corner.
There was just a little strip along there.
Campus Theater?
Campus Theater was down the end, right across from the dorm.
You notice my place is called Northgate.
This is the other Northgate.
But anyway, yeah, that was the exposure that you had to commercial enterprises.
Rarely did you go to Bryan.
I don't remember going to Bryan, not to sneeze at.
Do you remember any, I think this is a question that doesn't have application to your years,
Do you remember any major international or national events that caused you to kind of stop in your tracks and think about what it might mean to you?
Sputnik.
Oh, yeah.
Sputnik jumps out.
That's when that was, you know, it kind of shocked us in the reality that we're not necessarily on the cutting edge all the time on everything.
Not international, but a national event was when Barry Lyon decided to go to the University of Alabama.
Let's talk about Bear Bryant and football and so forth.
Did you as a student, did you have any acquaintance or interaction with any of those sports heroes?
Those guys were almost on another planet.
I didn't have any interaction with them except for Tyler.
He transferred to SMU, met a girl, transferred up there.
Charlie Milstead was a classmate.
And Charlie was there.
He'd come to hometown club meetings sometimes.
We knew each other vaguely.
I went to high school with him.
We didn't spend any time in the Corps.
I was athletic and going on.
I never went in the athletic block except just maybe walk in there or something.
I didn't know athletes to speak of.
Always had a great, great desire.
I'll never forget it.
The Letterman, in swimming and stuff, had those pretty white sweaters with that big maroon tee on it.
And swimming across the top of that tee.
I swam a lot because I was raised in State Park, a lifeguard, taught a lot of water safety and stuff.
But I wasn't a competitive swimmer.
But I had this great delusion.
fantasized about swimming, maybe even talked about going over there.
Now there's no way, there is no way that I look back that I would have done that.
But I would have killed to have worn one of those sweaters across that campus.
Because they meant, those guys were special because they were so dedicated to what they did.
In those days, you know, the era of jocks were a big thing anyway.
But we adored those guys.
I mean, they gave us headlines.
That's where we went and enjoyed ourselves, you know, football and stuff.
Did y'all have the perception that those athletes went to class and everything?
We had the perception they cheated a lot.
We had the perception they stole quizzes.
There was a guy named Murray Trimble, the one-armed guy that played down there that was infamous.
I think he may have flunked out one time, but he came back.
I remember seeing him.
I just couldn't, he's tough, tough old boys.
But that, we had, now, I wouldn't say that was universal.
Charlie Milstead was a smart guy.
He was an engineering major.
I knew him from high school.
I wouldn't say that it was, but we had the impression that those guys were cheap, you know, and stuff like that.
That may be overstating that.
What did people on campus think?
You and your buddies think about Bear Bryant?
Well, I was only exposed to him that one time.
But, you know, he was a tough son of a gun.
I watched practice with Slats a few times.
I went to practice with Phil.
And when somebody got hurt, I mean, he literally physically took them off.
I mean, he drug them off.
He'd get them out of the way.
He was a tough son of a gun.
And everybody knew it.
When he left, we felt like we were going to be betrayed.
I remember being sick about it.
Because you could tell that guy was going to have something out there that everybody's afraid of.
He had this mystique about him on campus and I think off campus.
Let's see.
See, we knew about Junction by then.
Junction happened a couple of years earlier.
Silver Taps as a student when you were there.
What was it, where was it, and what were your feelings about Silver Taps?
Silver Taps is a tradition that, for God's sake, I hope you never lose.
I don't know that it's unique, but it is as far as I know.
When I was a student, the tradition would adhere to the latter.
You might hear rumors, you usually would hear rumors of maybe something like you killed in a car wreck or something like that.
There were not that many of us.
We're talking about 7,000 people at the beginning of the year, you know, or maybe seven to eight.
And most of the time, you would either know the person or would have met that person.
And you certainly knew someone who knew that person, always.
It was not a, unless you shipped it so far that you didn't relate to it very closely.
So when you heard rumors of losing an Aggie somewhere, almost always you go to the flagpole at Sully's over in front of the academic building.
They had that plaque over there, that bronze plaque, and it had the name of the person and when the ceremony was going to be or whatever, announcing that.
Well, when the silver taps came, that was just what you did.
You know, it came time, and you'd turn your lights out, walk out of the dorm, never say a word.
And you'd hear those footsteps.
some coughing or sneezing or whatever, but you never heard a word.
It just was not done.
And I don't know that I remember anybody in our dorm that never went to self-defense.
I don't know that there was no one that did that, but I don't remember anybody doing that.
You get over there, and of course it was an eerie thing, but also a religious experience because, you know, most religions teach us that relationships are important.
And that's important to us.
And you lost one of yours, and that was a real emotional thing.
Coming back, you just gutted.
You know, you just, but you were aware that this was a memorial thing and that you could be next.
And you were reverent about that.
And when we got back to the dorm, we didn't have the blankets up.
and never turned any lights on.
For the most part, we had the blankets up, but I wouldn't say we never turned the light on when we got back to going to finish studying or something like that.
But for the most part, that wasn't the end of the day, for example, for us.
But everybody went, and they were reverent.
I had a chance to go to a silver tap.
My son was at A&M.
He finished in 92.
I guess it was the fall of 91 or something.
Went to a silver tap.
Related to the student body, poorly attended.
And of course, the commerce that goes on there, the roads and the highways out there, it was distracting because all that was going over on Welder and Road, things going on.
There were noises.
It used to be very quiet.
It was silent.
And you'd stand there with your thoughts until you heard the rifles and the vehicles and stuff.
Did you go to Muster as a student?
Went to Muster.
And you know, interestingly enough, I don't remember details about Muster.
Where was it held?
The one that jumps out in my mind was on the lawn out by the NSC.
They're the ones that I remember.
Now, I met the guy who was president of the Association of Farmer Students the year in 1959.
I'm sorry, I don't remember who he is.
But anyway, I remember his face.
I couldn't hear his name.
that you had noted over there.
But in any case, he was telling about that.
And I remember vaguely, because Association of Former Students was just part of what you did next.
Nothing was assumed, I guess, very much.
But we were not presumptuous about much.
When you graduated, you were going to be a former student.
You were going to be active in the Association of Former Students, at least financially.
Bonfire.
Where?
Over where it was until about three years ago, four years ago.
Make believe.
over by Duncan Hall over there south of Duncan.
And how big was it and how did it get to be big?
Well I don't remember how big it was.
It's always seemed big to me.
What was put in it?
Was it trash?
I don't remember trash.
Might have been.
I don't think it was.
I remember it being logs always but the outhouse on top seemed like I remember that forever.
Also, we had an Aggie that was either killed or got killed over there.
Right before I got to A&M, this guy working, and he was standing behind a car, and everyone came along and hit him, and he was killed.
That was kind of a, I remember that that was a thing that we remembered a lot about Bonfire.
It was a situation where you want to be careful if somebody had been killed over there.
The story's about, you know,
the tea servers trying to bomb it, you know, and set it on fire, and you know, some imposter being in there, and all that stuff.
But none of that happened during your...
It didn't happen.
I remember that that was talked about a lot, and it was a big thing we wouldn't dare to have, you know.
But non-regs were probably not as involved in bonfire in those days as we might should have been.
All right, Aggie Ring.
What was the, what was the routine for getting your... Gosh, that's what you work for.
I mean, when you got to A&M, you thought about your diploma after you got your Aggie ring.
I don't remember spending a lot of time thinking about getting my degree.
I spent time getting my hours for my autumn Aggie ring.
And when you get that ring or when we got it, it wasn't a ceremony.
Not like your association now.
You go upstairs and cope with it.
When you audit it and you go up there and get it, it's very uneventful, but you give them your ring.
And of course, you get it out and you walk down those steps looking at it.
You go to class, you couldn't even pay attention to what you were doing or watching your ring.
Of course, it looked like everybody else's, and you thought everybody's looking at your ring.
And it took a number of days to get past that, because you couldn't pay attention to what you were doing.
And of course, that thing has been symbolic forever.
How many people do we know because of that ring that you met somewhere here?
What is Aggie spirit?
Define it or explain it.
Well, that's just that spiritual thing, the spiritual meaning of the soul.
And I'm talking about things that make life more worth living.
It has to do with relationships.
And it has to do with what makes you care.
And I don't know how you define that very well.
There are things that make you passionate about things that other people don't have experiences, maybe, unless you weren't there.
What causes it to happen, I don't know.
It's the thing that we fear that will be lost.
It's something that can be not explained, but it can be passed on.
And it has to do with all these things we can talk about.
And I am firmly convinced that had I gone to school anyplace else that I would have had a good education and had very good friends.
But I am more convinced that I would have nothing like the life that I've lived.
I am totally convinced of that.
And I think most Aggies that have had an Aggie life like we have, you know, feel that way.
It has to do with the legacy in your family.
relationships all the way from the church that you go to.

If somebody jumps out, I mean, you may go to, you may live, I say this at graduation sometimes, you may have gone to school somewhere, and you may live in a neighborhood, or you may go to church, or you may live in a workplace, they may know you went to college somewhere, but if you went there, they know you went to that state.
And that is all part of that deal.
That's the exterior part of it.
There's more to it.
There's something about it that makes it, that's the thing that makes it hard and miserable, that difference.
Now, what is that?
I don't know.
Well, you've already gotten into that last question.
I think I said in advance, what did it mean to you that you attended A&M?
What effect did it have on you and your life?
What feelings do you have in your heart for A&M today?
Well, it's indescribable.
The gratitude, the debt that you feel is more than it can describe.
And obviously, I don't care how much money I ever made, if I gave it back, that would only be the financial part of it.
It would never, ever begin to describe or repay what my life experience has been.
It has meant that I've had a source of self-assurance and pride about who I am as a person.
It has given me financial...
ability in this life to far exceed anything beyond what you've ever dreamed of, ever, far, far.
And I'm not a rich man in monetary terms.
I'm comfortable with that.
